{{Refimprove|date=December 2006}} {{Infobox President | name = Bento Gonçalves da Silva | image = MuseuJulio10.jpg | caption = Bento Gonçalves. Unknown author, oil on canvas, 19th century. Museum Júlio de Castilhos | order = 1st [[Riograndense Republic|President of the Riograndense Republic]] | office = | vicepresident = [[:pt:José Gomes de Vasconcelos Jardim|José Gomes de Vasconcelos Jardim]] | term_start = 11 September 1836 | term_end = 1841 | predecessor = ''None'' ([[Empire of Brazil]]) | successor = José Gomes de Vasconcelos Jardim | spouse = Maria Tomásia Azambuja | children = | birth_date = September 23, 1788 | birth_place = [[Triunfo, Rio Grande do Sul|Triunfo]], [[Rio Grande do Sul]], [[Colonial Brazil|Brazil (Portuguese Colony)]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1847|7|18|1788|8|23}} | death_place = [[Guaíba|Pedras Brancas]], [[Empire of Brazil]] | party = Ragamuffin Party | religion = Roman Catholic | signature = | signature_alt = }} '''Bento Gonçalves''' (September 23, 1788 in [[Triunfo, Rio Grande do Sul|Triunfo]] &ndash; July 18, 1847 in [[Guaíba|Pedras Brancas]]), was an army officer, politician, monarchist and rebel leader of the [[Empire of Brazil]]. He was the first President of the [[Riograndense Republic]] and is considered by many to be one of the most important figures in the history of [[Rio Grande do Sul]].
Although a staunch monarchist,{{sfn|Rodrigues|1990|p=380}} Gonçalves led the rebel forces in the [[Ragamuffin War]]. Radicals within the rebel ranks forced the rebellion to become republican, something that Gonçalves opposed.{{sfn|Rodrigues|1990|p=372}} Still, even though he fought against the Empire, Gonçalves and his troops celebrated the birthday of the young Emperor Dom [[Pedro II of Brazil|Pedro II]].{{sfn|Rodrigues|1990|p=382}} After the conflict ended with the victory of the Empire, Gonçalves paid his respect to Pedro II by kissing his hand during the latter's trip to Rio Grande do Sul in December 1845.{{sfn|Rodrigues|1990|p=382}}
His main companions in arms during the rebellion were [[Antônio de Souza Neto]] and [[Giuseppe Garibaldi]].
